### getMangledTypeStr() {#ae174d348b8da903ca2da92129a963e11}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>static std::string getMangledTypeStr (<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/type">Type</a> &#42; Ty, bool &amp; HasUnnamedType)</>}
  labels = {["static"]}>
Returns a stable mangling for the type specified for use in the name mangling scheme used by &#39;any&#39; types in intrinsic signatures.

The mangling of named types is simply their name. Manglings for unnamed types consist of a prefix (&#39;p&#39; for pointers, &#39;a&#39; for arrays, &#39;f&#95;&#39; for functions) combined with the mangling of their component types. A vararg function type will have a suffix of &#39;vararg&#39;. Since function types can contain other function types, we close a function type mangling with suffix &#39;f&#39; which can&#39;t be confused with it&#39;s prefix. This ensures we don&#39;t have collisions between two unrelated function types. Otherwise, you might parse ffXX as f(fXX) or f(fX)X. (X is a placeholder for any other type.) The HasUnnamedType boolean is set if an unnamed type was encountered, indicating that extra care must be taken to ensure a unique name.

Definition at line <a href="#l00066">66</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/ir/intrinsics-cpp">Intrinsics.cpp</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

### lookupLLVMIntrinsicByName() {#ae071c2a56ff28186d5476e562811b2f7}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>static int lookupLLVMIntrinsicByName (<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/arrayref">ArrayRef</a>&lt; unsigned &gt; NameOffsetTable, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/stringref">StringRef</a> Name, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/stringref">StringRef</a> Target=&quot;&quot;)</>}
  labels = {["static"]}>
Looks up Name in NameTable via binary search.

NameTable must be sorted and all entries must start with &quot;llvm.&quot;. If NameTable contains an exact match for Name or a prefix of Name followed by a dot, its index in NameTable is returned. Otherwise, -1 is returned.

Definition at line <a href="#l00626">626</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/ir/intrinsics-cpp">Intrinsics.cpp</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

<Link id="l00054" /><CodeLine lineNumber="54"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Returns a stable mangling for the type specified for use in the name</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00055" /><CodeLine lineNumber="55"><Highlight kind="comment">/// mangling scheme used by &#39;any&#39; types in intrinsic signatures.  The mangling</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00056" /><CodeLine lineNumber="56"><Highlight kind="comment">/// of named types is simply their name.  Manglings for unnamed types consist</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00057" /><CodeLine lineNumber="57"><Highlight kind="comment">/// of a prefix (&#39;p&#39; for pointers, &#39;a&#39; for arrays, &#39;f&#95;&#39; for functions)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00058" /><CodeLine lineNumber="58"><Highlight kind="comment">/// combined with the mangling of their component types.  A vararg function</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00059" /><CodeLine lineNumber="59"><Highlight kind="comment">/// type will have a suffix of &#39;vararg&#39;.  Since function types can contain</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00060" /><CodeLine lineNumber="60"><Highlight kind="comment">/// other function types, we close a function type mangling with suffix &#39;f&#39;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00061" /><CodeLine lineNumber="61"><Highlight kind="comment">/// which can&#39;t be confused with it&#39;s prefix.  This ensures we don&#39;t have</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00062" /><CodeLine lineNumber="62"><Highlight kind="comment">/// collisions between two unrelated function types. Otherwise, you might</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00063" /><CodeLine lineNumber="63"><Highlight kind="comment">/// parse ffXX as f(fXX) or f(fX)X.  (X is a placeholder for any other type.)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00064" /><CodeLine lineNumber="64"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The HasUnnamedType boolean is set if an unnamed type was encountered,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00065" /><CodeLine lineNumber="65"><Highlight kind="comment">/// indicating that extra care must be taken to ensure a unique name.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
